"   <div id=\"basicsTopicLeft\">",
"    <div id=\"topicTitle\">",
"     Patient information: Maternal injuries from childbirth (The Basics)",
"    </div>",
"    <span class=\"view\">",
"     View in",
"     <a class=\"lang\" href=\"./es-419/maternal-injuries-from-childbirth-the-basics?source=topic_page\">",
"      Spanish",
"     </a>",
"    </span>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials\" href=\"./authors-and-editors/patient-information\">",
"     Written by the doctors and editors at UpToDate",
"    </a>",
"    <div id=\"topicText\">",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H24442705\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What are maternal injuries from childbirth?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Maternal injuries from childbirth are tears in the skin and muscle around the &ldquo;perineum.&rdquo; The perineum is the area between the opening of the vagina and the anus. Some of these injuries are minor and tear only the skin. Others are more serious and can tear skin and muscle. In some cases, the tear goes from the vagina to the anus. These injuries are also called &ldquo;perineal injuries.&rdquo;",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H24442720\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What causes maternal injuries from childbirth?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;These injuries happen when the perineum does not have time to stretch during labor. The baby&rsquo;s head or shoulders tear the perineum during birth. The tears are more likely to happen if:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        The baby is very large",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        The mother is giving birth for the first time",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        The doctor or midwife helps pull the baby out with a device that holds onto the baby&rsquo;s head. This might be done if the baby gets partly stuck in the birth canal.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      In the past, doctors and midwives sometimes cut the perineum to make the opening of the vagina larger. This is called an &ldquo;episiotomy.&rdquo; It was done to prevent maternal injuries during childbirth. But doctors and midwives now know that an episiotomy can make a woman MORE likely to have a tear near the perineum.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H24442736\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How are maternal injuries from childbirth treated?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Minor skin tears often need no treatment and heal on their own. If you have a tear that goes deeper, your doctor or midwife will use stitches to repair the tear. These stitches dissolve over time and do not need to be taken out.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H24442751\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What can I do to feel better while my injury heals?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Some people feel better if they:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Take &ldquo;sitz&rdquo; baths &ndash; This is a shallow, warm bath that helps clean and heal the vaginal area. Take them twice a day for 30 minutes each.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Take medicines to relieve pain, such as",
"        <a class=\"drug drug_patient\" href=\"UTD.htm?19/35/20021?source=see_link\">",
"         acetaminophen",
"        </a>",
"        (sample brand name: Tylenol&reg;) or",
"        <a class=\"drug drug_patient\" href=\"UTD.htm?14/17/14614?source=see_link\">",
"         ibuprofen",
"        </a>",
"        (sample brand names: Advil&reg;, Motrin&reg;).",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      If you got stitches for a serious tear, your doctor or midwife might recommend foods or medicines to keep your bowel movements soft. This makes you less likely to strain to push out a bowel movement, which might reopen the tear.",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      You shouldn&rsquo;t have sex until the tears heal. Sex can be painful and might reopen the tear.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H24442766\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Can maternal injuries from childbirth be prevented?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Sometimes. You are less likely to have a vaginal injury during childbirth if you control your pushing when you give birth. This helps the perineum to stretch slowly, making it less likely to tear.",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H24442781\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       More on this topic",
"      </span>",
"     </p>",
